South African Stocks: Anglo, Huge Group, Santam, Tiger Brands

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 
2011-06-01T15:46:16Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-01/south-african-stocks-anglo-huge-group-santam-tiger-brands.html
The FTSE/JSE  Africa  All Share Index
snapped six days of gains, losing 243.63, or 0.8 percent, to
32,322.10 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Anglo American Plc (AAL)  , the diversified mining company
that makes up 10 percent of  South Africa ’s benchmark stock
index, dropped the most since May 23, falling 6.25 rand, or 1.8
percent, to 335.25 rand. Copper declined the most in more than a
week, falling 1.3 percent to $9,093 a metric ton.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BIL SJ), the world’s biggest mining
company, retreated for a second day, losing 3.86 rand, or 1.4
percent, to 266.16 rand.  Blue Financial Services Ltd. (BFS)  , a provider of
unsecured loans, jumped the most since March 7, rallying 4
cents, or 14 percent, to 32 cents. Blue Financial posted a loss
of 275.6 million rand ($41 million) for the year ended February,
compared with a loss of 1.02 billion rand a year earlier, it
said in a statement today.  Huge Group Ltd. (HUG)  , a telecommunications company,
slipped 15 cents, or 13 percent, to 1.05 rand. Publication of
results will be delayed, Huge said in a trading update today. It
added that earnings for the year through February will be more
than 20 percent lower than a year earlier.  Lonrho Plc (LAF)  , an investment holding company with
infrastructure assets in Africa, declined the most since March
14, dropping 50 cents, or 24 percent, to 1.60 rand. Its loss
widened to 3.3 million pounds ($5.4 million) in the six months
through March from 1.7 million pounds a year earlier.  Santam Ltd. (SNT)  , South Africa’s largest property and
casualty insurer, dropped to the lowest since April 20, losing
1.50 rand, or 1.2 percent, to 124.50 rand. Commercial property
claims in the year to date increased as a result of flooding,
following the higher than normal summer rainfall in the northern
parts of the country, said Santam in a regulatory statement.  Tiger Brands Ltd. (TBS)  , South Africa’s biggest food
company, rose to the highest since January, climbing 5.14 rand,
or 2.7 percent, to 194.90 rand. Investec Plc raised the
company’s recommendation to “buy” from “hold.”  To contact the reporter on this story:
